["note","E6-S6",1774953183,"34dafe5f-6881-4bca-b209-c98c906e3550",{"msg":"Worktree + single-branch mode friction: When creating a code worktree for parallel task work, uncommitted ops (claim, heartbeat, etc.) written by the orchestrator in the main directory are invisible in the new worktree because .issues/ state is per-worktree at committed state only. Manual log copying was attempted but is fragile — it overwrites ops written by subagents back to the stale main-dir state. The architecture documents a .trellis/ ops worktree that would be shared across all code worktrees in two-branch mode, but in single-branch mode there is no such shared channel. Principle of least surprise violated: an agent that runs 'trls claim' then 'git worktree add' expects the claim to be visible in the new worktree, but it is not."}]
["note","E6-S6",1774953191,"34dafe5f-6881-4bca-b209-c98c906e3550",{"msg":"Related: the trls-worker SKILL instructs agents to use TRLS_LOG_SLOT for parallel subagents in worktrees, but gives no guidance for the simpler sequential case in single-branch mode. A worker using worktrees sequentially has no documented path for how to keep ops in sync — the skill gap leads agents to improvise (manual copy) in ways that break ops integrity. Suggested fix: trls-worker SKILL should document that in single-branch mode, either (a) avoid code worktrees and work directly on the feature branch, or (b) always run trls commands from the main directory and make code changes in the worktree, staging .issues/ from the main dir at commit time."}]
["heartbeat","E6-S1-T2",1774953281,"34dafe5f-6881-4bca-b209-c98c906e3550",{}]
["note","E6-S1-T2",1774953729,"34dafe5f-6881-4bca-b209-c98c906e3550",{"msg":"All three changes implemented with TDD: (1) fetchHTTP utility extracted to internal/sources/http.go, confluence.go and sharepoint.go refactored to use it; (2) MkdirAll errors propagated in both Materialize and MaterializeAndReturn in pipeline.go; (3) log slice pre-allocated with make([]Op,0,64) in ReadLogFromOffset. make check green: 100% mutation efficacy."}]
["decision","E6-S1-T2",1774953733,"34dafe5f-6881-4bca-b209-c98c906e3550",{"topic":"HTTP utility visibility","choice":"unexported fetchHTTP function","rationale":"Only used within the sources package by confluence and sharepoint providers; no need to export it. Keeps the API surface minimal."}]
["decision","E6-S1-T2",1774953737,"34dafe5f-6881-4bca-b209-c98c906e3550",{"topic":"Log slice pre-allocation size","choice":"initial capacity 64","rationale":"A fixed small capacity of 64 avoids multiple doublings for typical log files while keeping memory usage bounded. Cannot pre-allocate exact size without a two-pass scan."}]
["citation-accepted","E6-S1-T2",1774953743,"34dafe5f-6881-4bca-b209-c98c906e3550",{"confirmed_noninteractively":true,"rationale":"All three code quality improvements implemented with full TDD coverage. make check green with 100% mutation efficacy."}]
["transition","E6-S1-T2",1774953747,"34dafe5f-6881-4bca-b209-c98c906e3550",{"to":"done","outcome":"Extracted shared HTTP fetch utility into internal/sources/http.go (fetchHTTP), refactored confluence.go and sharepoint.go to delegate to it. Propagated os.MkdirAll errors in both Materialize and MaterializeAndReturn in pipeline.go. Pre-allocated log slice with make([]Op,0,64) in ReadLogFromOffset. All changes implemented TDD-first. make check fully green: lint clean, all tests pass, coverage ≥80%, mutation test efficacy 100%."}]
["transition","E6-S1",1774954207,"34dafe5f-6881-4bca-b209-c98c906e3550",{"to":"done","outcome":"Property tests for claim race resolution added (gopter, 4 tests, 100% mutation kill rate); HTTP fetch utility extracted from confluence/sharepoint; MkdirAll errors propagated in pipeline.go; log slice pre-allocated in ReadLogFromOffset."}]
["note","E6-S6",1774955907,"34dafe5f-6881-4bca-b209-c98c906e3550",{"msg":"Dual-branch migration finding: trls init --dual-branch creates the _trellis orphan branch and .trellis/ ops worktree, but does NOT migrate existing ops from the single-branch .issues/ directory. Migration requires manual copy of ops logs from the old location. trls init --dual-branch should either (a) detect existing ops and migrate them, or (b) emit a clear warning: 'existing ops found at .issues/ops/ — run trls migrate-ops to move them to the new location'. Without this, agents will see a fully empty issue database after the mode switch, with no error to explain why."}]
["note","E6-S6",1774955961,"34dafe5f-6881-4bca-b209-c98c906e3550",{"msg":"Transition artifact: PRs created under single-branch mode carry .issues/ops/ changes in the commit history. When merged to main, these land on the code branch — creating a divergence where main has a stale copy of ops alongside the authoritative _trellis branch. This is harmless in dual-branch mode (trls ignores .issues/ on main) but visually confusing. Clean dual-branch setup from the start would prevent this; a trls doctor rule that warns when .issues/ops/ exists on the code branch (and trellis.mode=dual-branch) would catch it going forward."}]
["note","E6-S6",1774956766,"34dafe5f-6881-4bca-b209-c98c906e3550",{"msg":"Hook gap: the architecture plans post-commit (heartbeat), post-merge (trls sync), and prepare-commit-msg (issue ID stamping) as convenience hooks, but has NO planned guardrail against ops commits landing on code branches. The architecture assumes dual-branch routing + .issues/.gitignore is sufficient. In practice, we needed a pre-commit enforcement hook to protect against: (1) migration from single-branch mode with stale tracked ops, (2) fresh clones without local git config set, (3) agents running trls from wrong directory. Our pre-commit hook deviates from the architecture philosophy of 'convenience, never enforcement' at the git layer — but the alternative (silent ops divergence) is worse. Recommend: architecture should explicitly address the migration path and fresh-clone scenario, either via a trls doctor check that warns and auto-repairs, or by acknowledging pre-commit enforcement as an optional hardening step for teams that care about ops integrity."}]
["note","E6-S6",1774956771,"34dafe5f-6881-4bca-b209-c98c906e3550",{"msg":"Hook gap: the architecture plans post-commit (heartbeat), post-merge (trls sync), and prepare-commit-msg (issue ID stamping) as convenience hooks, but has NO planned guardrail against ops commits landing on code branches. The architecture assumes dual-branch routing + .issues/.gitignore is sufficient. In practice, we needed a pre-commit enforcement hook to protect against: (1) migration from single-branch mode with stale tracked ops, (2) fresh clones without local git config set, (3) agents running trls from wrong directory. Our pre-commit hook deviates from the architecture philosophy of convenience-not-enforcement at the git layer. Recommend: architecture should address migration path and fresh-clone scenario, either via trls doctor auto-repair or by explicitly acknowledging pre-commit as an optional hardening step."}]
["note","E6-S6",1774956778,"34dafe5f-6881-4bca-b209-c98c906e3550",{"msg":"Hook gap: architecture plans post-commit/post-merge/prepare-commit-msg as convenience only, with no pre-commit guardrail against ops on code branches. Our pre-commit hook is enforcement-level, deviating from stated philosophy. Root cause: architecture assumes clean dual-branch setup from start; does not address migration or fresh-clone scenarios. Recommend trls doctor check and explicit hardening guidance."}]
["note","E6-S6",1774956783,"34dafe5f-6881-4bca-b209-c98c906e3550",{"msg":"Hook gap: architecture plans post-commit/post-merge/prepare-commit-msg as convenience only, with no pre-commit guardrail against ops on code branches. Our pre-commit hook is enforcement-level, deviating from stated philosophy. Root cause: architecture assumes clean dual-branch setup from start; does not address migration or fresh-clone scenarios. Recommend trls doctor check and explicit hardening guidance."}]
["note","E6-S6",1774956828,"34dafe5f-6881-4bca-b209-c98c906e3550",{"msg":"Hook gap: architecture plans post-commit/post-merge/prepare-commit-msg as convenience only, with no pre-commit guardrail against ops on code branches. Our pre-commit hook is enforcement-level, deviating from stated philosophy. Root cause: architecture assumes clean dual-branch setup from start; does not address migration or fresh-clone scenarios. Recommend trls doctor check and explicit hardening guidance. Secondary finding: pre-commit hooks fire in ALL worktrees sharing .git/hooks, including the _trellis ops worktree — hook must be branch-aware or it breaks trls ops commits."}]
["create","task-1774956949",1774956949,"34dafe5f-6881-4bca-b209-c98c906e3550",{"title":"Implement planned git hook templates (post-commit, post-merge, prepare-commit-msg)","parent":"E6-S6","type":"task","scope":[".issues/hooks/post-commit.sh.template",".issues/hooks/post-merge.sh.template",".issues/hooks/prepare-commit-msg.sh.template","cmd/trellis/init.go"],"definition_of_done":"Shell templates for all three hooks per architecture §11; trls init installs them into .git/hooks/; each hook is branch-aware (skips on _trellis); post-commit emits heartbeat and pushes ops in dual-branch mode; post-merge runs trls sync; prepare-commit-msg prepends active claim ID; pre-commit.sh.template branch-awareness documented as known gap","priority":"medium"}]
